                    </div>
                    <span>I'm just completely amazed about Buddhism. I'm wondering why I never took a Buddhism book before. I have the impulse since I was 16 (now I'm 25), but probably because I was afraid of change (like 99% of people) I just give up  the idea everytime it arised. Recently despair made me read and talk about  philosophy; finally, the first two (of the four) noble truths that Buddha  tougth exploded in my mind after reading it a in text, despair just  vanished. After reading The Art of Happiness (I recommend this book) I  started reading The Feeling Buddha. Well, this is really a piece of work of  book. Using Brazier's Buddhist methods you will discover things that never  tougth that were in your mind. My life become now an almost constant  meditation - like the same Dalai Lama itself suggest - you feel and  incredible joy to understand things as they happen. What made me write this  review is the suddenly discovery of a feeling I had for years and I never  ever analized before. I'll share this with you.  Everytime I have readed  any psicological text... in any book, just anything, I have an anoying  feeling inside of me. I was always completely apathic and spectic about  psicology. The funny thing is that when I choosed my career (software  engineering) I had Psicology in mind, because I really love it, even now  being software engineering I would like to be Psicologist...so.. I suppose  you got the deal here... :) Envy. I envy Psicologists!, because they are  Psicologists and I'm not....How I discovered this? Reading the Minnesota  Driver's manual, in a part that starts talking about conscience,  concentration, etc...  That's Buddhism about... enligthment anytime, any  moment, and any situation in your life. Analize any feeling, good or bad,  in the same moment of arising. It's a completely practice philosophy, it  will just change your life 180ยบ. Still you doesn't believe this is  possible? Well... it's shame, you are a wonderful human being, and you are  probably loosing the chance to live a mindfull life.</span>
                  
              
